{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3545e78c-ef15-4ccc-ac4b-5fbeb23d3f3b","content":"I don't have repository-specific documentation on this topic, but I can answer from .NET MAUI knowledge:\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This is **outdated**. It was a Xamarin.Forms API. In .NET MAUI, safe area insets are handled automatically by default on iOS — `ContentPage` already respects safe areas without any explicit property.\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This **does not exist** in .NET MAUI. It was also a Xamarin.Forms concept.\n\n### What to do in .NET MAUI (.NET 10):\n\n- **Safe area is respected by default** — no opt-in needed for content to avoid the notch/home indicator.\n- **For a full-bleed background image**, use padding overrides or place the image in an `AbsoluteLayout`/`Grid` that fills the page *behind* the safe content:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background image fills entire screen -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        <!-- Content respects safe area via padding -->\n        <Grid Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='0,47,0,34'}\">\n            <!-- your content here -->\n        </Grid>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr use `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific` for programmatic safe-area queries if needed.\n\n**TL;DR:** That tutorial is likely written for Xamarin.Forms. Neither property exists in .NET MAUI on .NET 10. Safe areas work automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ae431895-d503-4745-a94d-f8326e1f2e49","outputTokens":406,"requestId":"080B:25689:5A615:69448:69F2AB9F"},"id":"f3713aff-2cb6-43a0-a0f6-cfabb4992cf3","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:08:57.625Z","parentId":"df656fc7-3b0c-4ba4-af56-c03752043508"}
